						<summary>

						<p><hi rend="bold">King: Sakalalōkachchakravarttigaḷ Rājanārāyaṇa Sambhuvarāya (I) Year 7: (1345) A.D.</hi></p>						

						<p>Stone is not dressed and is carelessly engraved. It records that the <hi rend="italic">kaikkōḷa</hi>, who were residing at the temple precints <hi rend="italic">(tirumaḍai-viḷāgam)</hi> of the Tiruvāṉi-Īśvaran uḍaiya-nāyiṉār temple were under duress (on account of tax burden ?) and were forced to migrate and reside in an alien country. It is also stated that they were persuaded to return with the assurance that except five <hi rend="italic">paṇam</hi> of <hi rend="italic">kaḍamai</hi> and seven <hi rend="italic">paṇam</hi> of <hi rend="italic">vāsalvari</hi> no other tax would be levied on them.</p>						

						</summary>
